## Conversation
User asked to "formalize the weave attributes" to shape attributes.integration =
{name, version, meta} for integration tracking, then update integrations. This is
the bottom of a 5-PR Graphite stack splitting that work: (1) core [this commit],
(2) op-based Python integrations, (3) callback Python integrations, (4) agent OTel
processors, (5) TS SDK.

## What this slice does
- New module weave/integrations/integration_metadata.py: frozen dataclass
  IntegrationMetadata(name, version=WEAVE_VERSION, meta) + builders
  library_integration() / with_integration_metadata() / apply_integration_metadata().
  as_attributes() -> {"integration": {...}} (nested, for create_call paths).
  as_otel_attributes() -> flattened dotted keys (for OTel spans, slice 4); OTel
  attrs must be scalars so nested meta values are stringified.
- Generic op-level attributes: OpSettings.attributes + op(attributes=...) +
  Op protocol field. Stored as wrapper.attributes. _create_call merges
  func.attributes as the LOWEST-precedence base.

## Key decisions (don't "fix" these without reading)
- version = the INTEGRATING CODE's version (Weave SDK for built-ins), NOT the
  patched library version. Library version goes in meta.package_version. This
  matches the user's spec comment ("version of e.g. the weave SDK or claude code
  plugin version"). A future agent may be tempted to make version the lib version
  — that's wrong per spec.
- Precedence: op-level defaults are LOWEST. Codex review caught that injecting them
  into call_attrs (the __weave dict, which wins over context) would let op defaults
  override weave.attributes() — wrong. Fix: merge func.attributes as the base in
  _create_call BEFORE the context attrs, so user context wins on collision.
- 'weave' key rejected in op-level attributes (op() raises ValueError) because
  AttributesDict routes 'weave' into the reserved internal subdict.
- Chose generic op-level attributes over a dedicated 'integration' field so op.py
  stays integration-agnostic (no 'integration' magic key in core).

